Analysis Plan & Input Data

The aim of this project is to examine whether the data published in Gon√ßalves et al. (2014) supports the idea that first infections are more likely to involve severe disease than subsequent infections. In their paper, the authors report that the probability of severe disease given an infection is constant in the first few infections of life, i.e.¬†no immunity to severe disease is rapidly acquired (the null hypothesis). To test this conclusion we will use a binomial distribution using their reported overall probability of severe disease to determine the likelihood of obtaining the data they observed. The null hypothesis is rejected if the number of severe cases is two standard deviations above/below the mean calculated with the binomial model. In the paper, the number of severe episodes, severe/moderate episodes and the total number of infections is reported, forming the basis for this analysis:

goncalves_data <- data.frame("N_Infection"=seq(0,14),
                             "Severe"=c(0, 32, 18, 20, 9, 9, 2, 2, 8, NA, 1, NA, NA, NA, 1),
                             "Infections"=c(0, 715, 540, 424, 330, 267, 220, 168, 131, NA, 90, NA, NA, NA, 25),
                             "Susceptible"=c(102, 70, 52, 32, 23, 14, 12, 10, 2, 2, 1, 1, 1, 1, 0),
                             "Severe_Moderate"=c(0, 76, 41, 31, 15, 12, 5, 8, 5, 1, 1, 3, NA, NA, 1),
                             "Supp_Infections"=c(0, 715, 501, 369, 276, 213, 169, 120, 86, 62, 55, 47, NA, NA, 25))

The probability of severe disease

Dividing the number of severe disease cases by the total number of cases shows the probability of severe disease decreases somewhat with the order of infection, but it is not clear-cut. Severe/moderate disease risk appears to decrease more clearly. Note not all order of infection have an associated risk, because severe disease wasn‚Äôt always observed.

There was a mismatch in the number of total cases reported at 1st, 2nd, 3rd infections etc. I therefore included both denominators for summary value calculation to test six ‚Äúoverall probabilities‚Äù of severe/moderate disease:

  1. the sum of severe cases divided by the sum of total cases: 0.0361
  2. the median of all non-zero probabilities (fractions) shown in the red bar graph above: 0.0335
  3. the sum of all moderate/severe cases divided by the sum of cases reported in the supplementary: 0.0802
  4. the median of all non-zero probabilities (fractions) shown in the blue bar graph above: 0.0691
  5. the sum of all moderate/severe cases divided by the sum of cases reported in the main paper: 0.0721
  6. the median of all non-zero probabilities (fractions) of moderate/severe disease using the main paper denominators: 0.0593

Given each of these probabilities, we ask how often one would observe severe disease, if X number of malaria cases were recorded, where X is the number of observations for each order of infection. This process is repeated 10,000 times to obtain means and 95% confidence intervals.

The plot below shows the distribution of simulated results as violin plots. The area of 1.96 standard deviations (95% confidence interval) is shaded light grey with the mean in black. The actual values observed in the paper are shown in red for severe cases and blue for moderate/severe cases. For severe cases, the observed value is within the 95% confidence interval, but only just- moderate/severe cases are outwith the 95% confidence interval in first infection regardless of how the mean/median probability was calculated.

## Linear Regression on Severe / Moderate Risk Fractions

To quantify how the risk evolves as a function of previous exposure we can use generalised linear models. We will use the number of severe or severe/moderate cases as our dependent variable, respectively and order of infection as our independent variable. Order of infection can be modelled a number of ways: categorically or continuously, and linearly or quadratically. We will use Akaike‚Äôs Information Criterion (AIC) to compare model fit and will choose the model with the lowest AIC if \(\Delta AIC \geq 2\) if the difference is smaller we will select the more parsimonious model.

model selection results
model_formula aic n_infection_coef
Severe/Infections ~ N_Infection_Words 47.88716 -0.6229922
Severe/Infections ~ N_Infection 49.37997 -0.0800162
Severe/Infections ~ N_Infection + I(N_Infection^2) 50.03279 -0.3045299
Severe_Moderate/Supp_Infections ~ N_Infection_Words 65.13036 0.0994339
Severe_Moderate/Supp_Infections ~ N_Infection 55.53736 -0.1432331
Severe_Moderate/Supp_Infections ~ N_Infection + I(N_Infection^2) 56.13001 -0.2670400
Severe_Moderate/Infections ~ N_Infection_Words 52.32640 0.1704871
Severe_Moderate/Infections ~ N_Infection 45.61410 -0.2074043
Severe_Moderate/Infections ~ N_Infection + I(N_Infection^2) 45.80371 -0.4070035

From these results we can conclude that modelling N_Infection continuously and linearly is the way to go.
